\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The algorithm is simply this.
 Start with finding the maximum of the probability density function, call
 it 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\text{max}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then construct an interval from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\text{max}}$
\end_inset

 and successively choose a point in this interval, and move in constant
 steps; at some iteration, call this point 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Next, construct random numbers uniformly in the relevant range (over which
 the PDF is defined; viz.
 the relevant domain if you're fussy).
 Let's call it for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then check if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)>h$
\end_inset

.
 If it is, then you accept this point (save it in some array that'll represent
 the set of points which follow the said distribution).
 Else you reject the point.
 Repeat this a fixed number of times for each 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 The claim is the set of points you get will satisfy the same PDF.
 Why it works is intuitively obvious.
 Start with considering 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0$
\end_inset

.
 All points are accepted.
 Then as 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 increases, fewer and fewer points are accepted; viz.
 those which are more likely according to the PDF, get more representation
 in the final set of points.
 This is readily generalizable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is however a major draw back.
 How many particles you'll have in the final array is stochastic in this
 algorithm.
 However, this can be easily fixed.
 Consider the further generalization.
 Find 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 uniform randomly and then find 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 uniformly randomly as stated.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is accepted, good else repeat till you have enough particles.
 Because of the stochastic nature of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 sequentially, or selecting it randomly, both are equivalent.
 The latter however allows for an obvious way of fixing the number of particles.
\end_layout

